dspace-development.title: Princeton to test registered reports in Elements

comments.body:
There do seem to be problems in attempting to generate the reports for user activity from the newly-migrated Digital Science production deployment `princeton.elements.symplectic.org`. Please compare a report generated for user publication claims from the legacy deployment `oaworkflow.princeton.edu` with the same from `princeton.elements.symplectic.org`:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/c59b3b35-c325-4d0b-92da-23f74d432f12)
![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/76e5bc75-437d-468d-9808-05a293a241f6)
An enquiry has been made on Basecamp with the following: https://3.basecamp.com/3804430/buckets/26643531/todos/4720742014#__recording_5184814460

The errors encountered for `https://dev.princeton.elements.symplectic.org:8092/secure-api/v5.5` do not seem to have been resolved. I have attempted to reconfigure the endpoint for the same port as the `production` environment (using `https://dev.princeton.elements.symplectic.org:8091/secure-api/v5.5`), however, this did not prove effective either.

I am not certain as to why this is failing on CircleCI, I am going to request shell access to the build container:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/182207331-042dd7c5-ff93-4c32-976a-f3200dfc5c61.png)

This is likely an issue with the CircleCI container, as I am finding the following:

```
circleci@be0d4fc85bc3:~/project$ ruby --version
ruby 2.6.3p62 (2019-04-16 revision 67580) [x86_64-linux]
```

https://github.com/pulibrary/etd_transformer/blob/main/.circleci/config.yml#L3 is using the deprecated `circleci/ruby` containers series (these were deprecated in favor of `cimg/ruby`. I can look to issue a pull request addressing this.
This seems to be progressing on https://app.circleci.com/pipelines/github/pulibrary/etd_transformer?branch=update-circleci-image

comments.body: @faithc can you add a "sudden priority" reasoning to this ticket that would justify it being done before the next work cycle? Thanks!

This website feature serves as a way in which we are trying to mitigate both harmful language and content in archival collections. We'd like to know as soon as possible if a user encounters harmful language or content of which we're not aware in order to address it in a timely manner, and we would like the language associated with this feedback mechanism to be as clear as possible. Currently, it does not address the issue of harmful content. Thanks.
